<subSubSection id="8DDE654F0117D64CFF0F0F9FFAB2FCAE" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph id="C57B36C40117D64DFF0F0F9FFEC2FA58" blockId="4.[151,505,1471,1532]" box="[151,273,1506,1532]" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
(
<figureCitation id="5DFF2A410117D64DFF070F9FFED4FA58" box="[159,263,1506,1532]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1652,1676]" captionTargetBox="[499,1093,834,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-307@3.[483,1103,829,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Megaselia males: (5) M. maculafemoralis left face of hypopygium; (6) M. necscabra left face of hypopygium; (7) M. necscabra left notopleuron (N = notopleural cleft. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5134033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5134033/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">Figs 6–7</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C57B36C40117D64DFF0F0C4FFCDAF960" blockId="4.[151,1436,1586,2012]" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation id="A1554B350117D64DFED90C4FFDF1F9E8" author="Borgmeier, T." box="[321,546,1586,1612]" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" pagination="81 - 276" refId="ref6066" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1967 b) Studies on Indo-Australian phorid flies, based mainly on material of the Museum of Comparative Zoology and the United States National Museum. Part II. Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 10, 81 - 276." type="journal article" year="1967">Borgmeier (1967b)</bibRefCitation>
this will run to couplet 10, Lead 2 on page 93, to 
<taxonomicName id="02C44D470117D64DFBEC0C4EFAAFF9E8" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1967" box="[1140,1404,1586,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copiosa">
<emphasis id="F7B0EAD60117D64DFBEC0C4EFB24F9E8" box="[1140,1271,1587,1612]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">M. copiosa</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
or to couplet 51, lead 1, on page 89, to 
<taxonomicName id="02C44D470117D64DFDDF0C26FC3EF9D0" authority="Borgmeier. However" authorityName="Borgmeier. However" authorityYear="1967" box="[583,1005,1626,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curticauda">
<emphasis id="F7B0EAD60117D64DFDDF0C26FD3EF9D0" box="[583,749,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">M. curticauda</emphasis>
Borgmeier. However
</taxonomicName>
, both these species have a yellowish abdominal venter. Some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="02C44D470117D64DFDF80CFEFD04F938" box="[608,727,1667,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis id="F7B0EAD60117D64DFDF80CFEFD04F938" box="[608,727,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">M. scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the subsequenly described 
<taxonomicName id="02C44D470117D64DFBC90CFEFAE4F938" authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1994" box="[1105,1335,1666,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pleurota">
<emphasis id="F7B0EAD60117D64DFBC90CFEFB08F938" box="[1105,1243,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">M. pleurota</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
will run to the same couplets, but both lack a notopleural cleft
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C57B36C40117D64DFF5E0CAFFCA0F948" blockId="4.[151,1436,1586,2012]" box="[198,883,1746,1772]" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
The name refers to the resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="02C44D470117D64DFD150CAEFCA0F948" authority="Schmitz." authorityName="Schmitz." box="[653,883,1746,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis id="F7B0EAD60117D64DFD150CAEFCD0F948" box="[653,771,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">M. scabra</emphasis>
Schmitz.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C57B36C40117D64CFF5E0C87FAB2FCAE" blockId="4.[151,1436,1586,2012]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,152,858]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="4" pageNumber="61">
Male. Frons brown, clearly broader than long, with 80–90 hairs and dense but very fine microsetae. SAs almost equal, the lower pair being only slightly shorter. The antials lower on frons than anterolaterals, and about level with an upper SA and as far from the latter as from an AL bristle. Pre-ocellars closer together than upper SAs and about as far apart as either is from a mediolateral bristle, which is at about the same level on frons. Cheek with 2 bristles and jowl with two longer and more robust ones. The subglobose postpedicels brown (but not dark), with about 20 SPS vesicles. Palps straw yellow, at most a third as broad as postpedicel, with 3 longer and 3 shorter bristles and 4–5 hairs. Labrum pale and about twice as wide as a palp. Labella together about 1.3x as wide as postpedicel, light brown and with very few short spinules below. Thorax brown. Two notopleural bristles and an inconspicuous cleft in front of these (
<figureCitation id="5DFF2A410116D64CFBCC0A95FB72FEA6" box="[1108,1185,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1652,1676]" captionTargetBox="[499,1093,834,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-307@3.[483,1103,829,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Megaselia males: (5) M. maculafemoralis left face of hypopygium; (6) M. necscabra left face of hypopygium; (7) M. necscabra left notopleuron (N = notopleural cleft. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5134033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5134033/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs (at most as long as those in middle of scutum) and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with hairs mainly towards sides and at rear margins (
<figureCitation id="5DFF2A410116D64CFB320B45FB20FEF6" box="[1194,1267,312,338]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1652,1676]" captionTargetBox="[499,1093,834,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-307@3.[483,1103,829,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Megaselia males: (5) M. maculafemoralis left face of hypopygium; (6) M. necscabra left face of hypopygium; (7) M. necscabra left notopleuron (N = notopleural cleft. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5134033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5134033/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Venter greyish brown, and with hairs on segments 3–6 (
<figureCitation id="5DFF2A410116D64CFD020B1DFD31FEDE" box="[666,738,352,378]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1652,1676]" captionTargetBox="[499,1093,834,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-307@3.[483,1103,829,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Megaselia males: (5) M. maculafemoralis left face of hypopygium; (6) M. necscabra left face of hypopygium; (7) M. necscabra left notopleuron (N = notopleural cleft. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5134033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5134033/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Hypopygium brown, with a pale brown anal tube, whitish yellow hypandrial lobes, and as 
<figureCitation id="5DFF2A410116D64CFD950BF5FD87FE06" box="[525,596,392,418]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1652,1676]" captionTargetBox="[499,1093,834,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-307@3.[483,1103,829,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Megaselia males: (5) M. maculafemoralis left face of hypopygium; (6) M. necscabra left face of hypopygium; (7) M. necscabra left notopleuron (N = notopleural cleft. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5134033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5134033/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="62">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
. The right hypandrial lobe clearly smaller than that of the left. With four rectal papillae. Legs straw yellow apart from light brown hind femora, a brownish tinge to mid femur and tibia and to hind tibia, and brown patch on mid coxa. Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 a little longer than 4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about three quarters of its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half. Hind tibia with 7–9 differentiated posterodorsal hairs and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings 0.9–1.0 mm long. Costal index 0.43– 0.44. Costal ratios 2.4: 1.4–1.5: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity id="023C9B210116D64CFCFF0805FC1CFD36" box="[871,975,632,658]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
long. Hair at base of vein 3 well developed (subequal to costal cilia of section 3). With 1–2 axillary bristles shorter than costal cilia. Sc obscure and not reaching R1. Thick veins light brown, thin veins 4–6 dark grey and 7 pale. Membrane tinged brownish grey (evident to naked eye when viewed against a white background). Haltere with whitish yellow knob.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
